# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-motors-corporation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The **1979 oil crisis**, sometimes referred to as the **second oil crisis** (in reference to the 1973 oil crisis), refers to the drop in oil production in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution that led to an energy crisis in 1979.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Although the global oil supply only decreased by approximately four percent, the oil markets' reaction raised the price of crude oil drastically over the next 12 months, more than doubling it to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3), equivalent to $175 per barrel ($1,101/m3) in 2025.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The sudden increase in price was connected with fuel shortages similar to the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, following the onset of the Iran–Iraq War, oil production in Iran fell drastically.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Iraq's oil production also dropped significantly, triggering economic recessions worldwide.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices did not return to pre-crisis levels until the mid-1980s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Oil prices after 1980 began a steady decline over the next 20 years, except for a brief uptick during the Gulf War, which then reached a 60% fall-off in the 1990s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Mexico, Nigeria, and Venezuela's major oil exporters expanded their production during this time.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The Soviet Union became the largest oil producer in the world, and oil from the North Sea and Alaska flooded the market.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1978, a strike by 37,000 workers at Iran's nationalized oil refineries reduced production from 6 million barrels (950,000 m3) per day to about 1.5 million barrels (240,000 m3).
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] By bringing navy personnel into crude oil production operations, the government fixed short-term disruptions and by end of November the output came back to almost normal level.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] On January 16, 1979, the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, and his wife, Farah Pahlavi, left Iran at the behest of Prime Minister Shapour Bakhtiar, who sought to calm the situation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] After the departure of the Shah, Ayatollah Khomeini became the new leader of Iran.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The rise in oil prices benefited a few members of the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC), which made record profits.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Under the new Iranian government, oil exports later resumed but production was inconsistent and at a lower volume, further raising prices.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia and other OPEC nations, under the presidency of Mana Al Otaiba, increased production to offset most of the decline, and by early 1979 the overall loss in worldwide production was roughly four percent.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The war between Iran and Iraq in 1980 caused a further 7 percent drop in worldwide production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] OPEC production was surpassed by other exporters such as the United States, as OPEC member nations were divided amongst themselves.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Saudi Arabia, a "swing producer", tried to gain back the market share after 1985, increasing production and causing downward pressure on prices, making high-cost oil production facilities less profitable.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The oil crisis had a mixed impact on the United States.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Richard Nixon had imposed price controls on domestic oil as a result of the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Since then, gasoline price controls had been repealed, but those on domestic oil remained.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The Jimmy Carter administration began a phased deregulation of oil prices on April 5, 1979, when the average price of crude oil was US$15.85 per barrel ($100/m3).
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Starting with the Iranian revolution, the price of crude oil rose to $39.50 per barrel ($248/m3) over the next 12 months (its all-time highest real price until March 3, 2008).
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Deregulating domestic oil price controls allowed U.S. oil output to rise sharply from the large Prudhoe Bay fields, while oil imports fell sharply.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Although not directly related, the near-disaster at Three Mile Island on March 28, 1979, also increased anxiety about energy policy and availability.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Due to memories of the oil shortage in 1973, motorists soon began panic buying, and long lines appeared at gas stations, as they had six years earlier.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The average vehicle of the time consumed between two and three liters (about 0.5–0.8 gallons) of gasoline an hour while idling, and it was estimated that Americans wasted up to 150,000 barrels (24,000 m3) of oil per day idling their engines in the lines at gas stations.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In 1979, the amount of oil sold in the United States was only 3.5 percent less than the record set for oil sold in 1978.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] A telephone poll of 1,600 American adults conducted by the Associated Press and NBC News and released in early May 1979 found that only 37 percent of Americans thought the energy shortages were real, nine percent were not sure, and 54 percent thought the energy shortages were a hoax.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Many politicians proposed gas rationing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] One such proponent was Harry Hughes, Governor of Maryland, who proposed odd-even rationing (only people with an odd-numbered license plate could purchase gas on an odd-numbered day), as was used during the 1973 Oil Crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Several states implemented odd-even gas rationing, including California, Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey, Oregon, and Texas.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Coupons for gasoline rationing were printed but were never actually used during the 1979 crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] On July 15, 1979, President Carter outlined his plans to reduce oil imports and improve energy efficiency in his "Crisis of Confidence" speech, sometimes known as the "malaise" speech.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In the speech, Carter encouraged citizens to do what they could to reduce their use of energy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] He had already installed water tank heating solar panels on the roof of the White House and a wood-burning stove in the living quarters.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The panels were removed in 1986, reportedly for roof maintenance, during the administration of his successor, Ronald Reagan.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] A speech Carter gave in April 1977 argued that the oil crisis was "the moral equivalent of war".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In November 1979, Iranian revolutionaries seized the American Embassy, and Carter imposed an embargo on Iranian oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In January 1980, he issued the Carter Doctrine, declaring: "An attempt by any outside force to gain control of the Persian Gulf region will be regarded as an assault on the vital interests of the United States".
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Additionally, as part of his administration's efforts at deregulation, Carter proposed removing price controls that had been imposed by the Richard Nixon administration before the 1973 crisis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Carter agreed to remove price controls in phases.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] They were fully dismantled in 1981 under Reagan.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Carter also said he would impose a windfall profit tax on oil companies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] While the regulated price of domestic oil was kept to $6 a barrel, the world market price was $30.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In 1980, the U.S. government established the Synthetic Fuels Corporation to produce an alternative to imported fossil fuels.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] When the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil increased 250 percent between 1978 and 1980, the oil-producing areas of Texas, Oklahoma, Louisiana, Colorado, Wyoming, and Alaska began experiencing an economic boom and population inflows.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] According to a 2019 study, individuals who were between the ages of 15 and 18 during the 1979 oil crisis were substantially less likely to use cars once they were in their mid-30s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] In response to the high oil prices of the 1970s, industrial nations took steps to reduce their dependence on the Organization of Petroleum-Exporting Countries (OPEC) oil.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Electric utilities worldwide switched from oil to coal, natural gas, or nuclear power.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] National governments initiated multibillion-dollar research programs to develop alternatives to oil and commercial exploration developed major non-OPEC oilfields in Siberia, Alaska, North Sea, and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] By 1986, daily worldwide demand for oil dropped by 5 million barrels but, non-OPEC production rose by an even-larger amount.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Consequently, OPEC's market share reduced from 50 percent in 1979 to 29 percent in 1985.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] At the time, Detroit's "Big Three" automakers (Ford, Chrysler, GM) were marketing downsized full-sized automobiles like the Chevrolet Caprice, the Ford LTD Crown Victoria and the Dodge St.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Regis which met the CAFE fuel economy mandates passed in 1978.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit's response to the growing popularity of imported compacts like the Toyota Corolla and the Volkswagen Rabbit was the Chevrolet Citation and the Ford Fairmont.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Ford replaced the Ford Pinto with the Ford Escort and Chrysler, on the verge of bankruptcy, introduced the Dodge Aries K.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] GM was having unfavorable market reactions to the Citation and introduced the Chevrolet Corsica and Chevrolet Beretta in 1987 which sold better.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] GM also replaced the Chevrolet Monza, introducing the 1982 Chevrolet Cavalier which was better received.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Ford experienced a similar market rejection of the Fairmont and introduced the front-wheel-drive Ford Tempo in 1984.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Detroit was not well prepared for the sudden rise in fuel prices, and imported brands, primarily the Asian models, which were mass-marketed and had a lower manufacturing cost as opposed to British and West German brands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] A year after the 1979 Iranian Revolution, Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Japanese exports later displaced the automotive market once dominated by lower-tier European manufacturers (Renault, Fiat, Opel, Peugeot, MG, Triumph, Citroen).
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Triumph, Simca) or withdraw from the U.S. market, especially in the wake of grey market automobiles or the inability of the vehicle to meet DOT requirements, from emission requirements to automotive lighting.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] Many imported brands utilized fuel-saving technologies such as fuel injection and multi-valve engines over the common use of carburetors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] The overall fuel economy of cars in the United States increased from about 15 miles per US gallon (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) in 1979 to 18 mpg‑US (13 L/100 km; 22 mpg‑imp) by 1985 and 20 mpg‑US (12 L/100 km; 24 mpg‑imp) by 1990.
[src:american-motors-corporation/1979-oil-crisis] This was one factor leading to the subsequent 1980s oil glut.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The program began in 1968 as a bi-weekly television show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The two sat on opposite sides of the cream-colored set, though the set's color was later changed to black, the color still in use.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The show used a large stopwatch during transition periods and highlighted its topics through chroma key—both techniques are still used.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In 1972, the program began airing from 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time, although this time was sometimes disrupted by broadcasting of NFL games on Sundays.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Since then, the show has generally kept the Sunday evening format, although the start time has occasionally been shifted.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The program generally starts at 7:00 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] If sports programming is airing that afternoon, *60 Minutes* starts at 7:30 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The show is hosted by correspondents who do not share screen time with each other.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Full-time hosts include Lesley Stahl and Bill Whitaker.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Several spinoffs have been made, including international formats of the show.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Starting in 2006, the background color was changed to red, the title text color changed to white, and the stopwatch was shifted to the upright position.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The program employed a magazine format similar to that of the Canadian program *W5*, which had premiered two years earlier.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] It pioneered many of the most important investigative journalism procedures and techniques, including re-editing interviews, hidden cameras, and "gotcha journalism" visits to the home or office of an investigative subject.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Similar programs sprang up in Australia and Canada during the 1970s, as well as on local television news.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Initially, *60 Minutes* aired as a bi-weekly show hosted by Mike Wallace and Harry Reasoner debuting on September 24, 1968, and alternating weeks with other CBS News productions on Tuesday evenings at 10:00 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A meditation by Wallace and Reasoner on the relation between perception and reality.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Wallace said that the show aimed to "reflect reality".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The first "magazine-cover" chroma key was a photo of two helmeted policemen (for the Clark interview segment).
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Wallace and Reasoner sat in chairs on opposite sides of the set, which had a cream-colored backdrop; the more famous black backdrop (which is still used as of 2020) did not appear until the following year.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The logo was in Helvetica type with the word "Minutes" spelled in all lower-case letters; the logo most associated with the show (rendered in Eurostile type with "Minutes" spelled in uppercase) did not appear until about 1974.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Further, to extend the magazine motif, the producers added a "Vol. xx, No. xx" to the title display on the chroma key; modeled after the volume and issue number identifications featured in print magazines, this was used until about 1971.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The trademark stopwatch, however, did not appear on the inaugural broadcast; it would not debut until several episodes later.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Alpo dog food was the sole sponsor of the first program.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Don Hewitt, who had been a producer of the *CBS Evening News* with Walter Cronkite, sought out Wallace as a stylistic contrast to Reasoner.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] According to one historian of the show, the idea of the format was to make the hosts the reporters, to always feature stories that were of national importance but focused upon individuals involved with, or in conflict with, those issues, and to limit the reports' airtime to around 13 minutes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] However, the initial season was troubled by lack of network confidence, as the program did not garner ratings much higher than that of other CBS News documentaries.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* struggled under that stigma during its first three years.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Changes to *60 Minutes* came fairly early in the program's history.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] When Reasoner left CBS to co-anchor ABC's evening newscast (he would return to CBS and *60 Minutes* in 1978), Morley Safer joined the team in 1970, and he took over Reasoner's duties of reporting less aggressive stories.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] By 1971, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) introduced the Prime Time Access Rule, which freed local network affiliates in the top 50 markets (in practice, the entire network) to take a half-hour of prime time from the networks on Mondays through Saturdays and one full hour on Sundays.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] After a six-month hiatus in late 1971, CBS found a prime place for *60 Minutes* in a portion of that displaced time, 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Central Time) on Sundays in January 1972.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] This proved somewhat less than satisfactory, however, because in order to accommodate CBS telecasts of late afternoon National Football League (NFL) games, *60 Minutes* went on hiatus during the fall from 1972 to 1975 (and the summer of 1972).
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] This took place because football telecasts were protected contractually from interruptions in the wake of the infamous "Heidi Bowl" incident on NBC in November 1968.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Eventually, during the summers of 1973 through 1975, CBS did allow the program back onto the prime time schedule proper, on Fridays in 1973 and Sundays the two years thereafter, as a replacement for programs aired during the regular television season.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] It was only when the FCC returned an hour to the networks on Sundays (for news or family programming), which had been taken away from them four years earlier, in a 1975 amendment to the Access Rule, that CBS finally found a viable permanent timeslot for *60 Minutes*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] When the family-oriented drama *Three for the Road* ended after a 12-week run in the fall, the news magazine took its place at 7:00 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] This move, and the addition of then-White House correspondent Dan Rather to the reporting team, made the program into a strong ratings hit and, eventually, a general cultural phenomenon.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] This was no less than a stunning reversal of the historically poor ratings performances of documentary programs on network television.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] By 1976, *60 Minutes* became the top-rated program on Sunday nights in the US.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] By 1979, it had achieved the #1 spot among all television programs in the Nielsen ratings, unheard of before for a news broadcast in prime time.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] This success translated into great profits for CBS; advertising rates increased from $17,000 per 30-second spot in 1975 to $175,000 in 1982.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The program sometimes does not start until after 7:00 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Eastern, due largely to CBS Sports live sporting events.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] At the conclusion of an NFL game, *60 Minutes* will air in its entirety and delay all subsequent programs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] However, in the Pacific time zone, *60 Minutes* is always able to start at its scheduled time as live sports coverage ends earlier in the afternoon.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Starting in the 2012–2013 season, in order to accommodate a new NFL scheduling policy that the second game of a doubleheader start at 4:25 p.m., CBS changed the scheduled start time of *60 Minutes* to 7:30 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Eastern time (or game conclusion) for Eastern and Central Time Zone stations which are receiving a game in that window.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Eastern/Pacific (or game conclusion if a late single game is airing in the eastern markets) on stations which are not broadcasting a late game in a given week (or for Western time zones even if a doubleheader airs).
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Since the 2023–2024 season, the show began to have occasional 90-minute episodes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] For most of the 1970s, the program included *Point/Counterpoint*, in which a liberal and conservative commentator debated an issue.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] This segment originally featured James J.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Kilpatrick representing the conservative side and Nicholas von Hoffman for the liberal, with Shana Alexander taking over for von Hoffman after he departed in 1974.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The segment was an innovation that caught the public imagination as live versions of competing editorials.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In 1979, Alexander asked Hewitt to raise the $350 per week pay; Hewitt declined, and the segment ended.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A similar concept was revived briefly in March 2003 featuring Bob Dole and Bill Clinton, former opponents in the 1996 presidential election.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The pair agreed to do ten segments (titled *Clinton/Dole* and *Dole/Clinton* in alternating weeks), but these did not continue into the 2003–2004 fall season.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Reports indicated that the segments were considered too gentlemanly, in the style of the earlier *Point/Counterpoint*, and lacked the feistiness of *Crossfire*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] From 1978 to 2011, the program usually ended with (usually light-hearted and humorous) commentary by Andy Rooney expounding on topics of wildly varying importance, ranging from international politics, to economics, and his personal philosophy on everyday life.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] One recurring topic was measuring the amount of coffee in coffee cans.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Rooney's pieces, particularly one in which he referred to actor Mel Gibson as a "wacko", on occasion led to complaints from viewers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] After four weeks without Rooney, *60 Minutes* lost 20% of its audience.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] CBS management concluded that it was in their best interest to have Rooney return immediately.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Rooney published several books documenting his contributions to the program, including *Years of Minutes* and *A Few Minutes with Andy Rooney*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Rooney retired from *60 Minutes*, delivering his final commentary on October 2, 2011; it was his 1,097th commentary over his 34-year career on the program.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] He died one month later on November 4, 2011.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On November 13, 2011, *60 Minutes* featured an hour-long tribute to Rooney and his career and included a rebroadcast of his final commentary segment.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The opening sequence features a *60 Minutes* "magazine cover" with the show's trademark, an Aristo stopwatch, intercut with preview clips of the episode's stories.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The sequence ends with each of the correspondents and hosts introducing themselves.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The last host who appears then says, "Those stories tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] When Rooney was a prominent fixture, the final line was "Those stories and Andy Rooney, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Before that, and whenever Rooney did not appear, the final line was "Those stories and more, tonight on *60 Minutes*".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The stopwatch counts off each of the broadcast's 60 minutes, starting from zero at the beginning of each show.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] It is seen during the opening title sequence, before each commercial break, and at the tail-end of the closing credits, and each time it appears it displays (within reasonable accuracy) the elapsed time of the episode to that point.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On October 29, 2006, the opening sequence changed from a black background, which had been used for over a decade, to white.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Also, the gray background for the Aristo stopwatch in the "cover" changed to red, the color for the title text changed to white, and the stopwatch itself changed from the diagonal position it had been oriented in for 31 years to an upright position.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Videos and transcripts of *60 Minutes* editions, as well as clips that were not included in the broadcast are available on the program's website.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In September 2010, the program launched a website called "60 Minutes Overtime", in which stories broadcast on-air are discussed in further detail.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Previously the show had a partnership with Yahoo! for distribution of extra content.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Based on viewership ratings, *60 Minutes* is the most successful program in American television history since it was moved into its present timeslot in 1975.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* was a top ten show for 23 seasons in a row (1977–2000), an unsurpassed record, and has made the Top 20 for every season since the 1976–1977 season, except from 2005 to 2008.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On November 16, 2008, the edition featuring an interview with President-elect Barack Obama, earned a total viewership of 25.1 million viewers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On October 6, 2013, the broadcast (which was delayed by 44 minutes that evening due to a Denver Broncos–Dallas Cowboys NFL game) drew 17.94 million viewers; retaining 63% of the 28.32 million viewers of its lead-in, and making it the most watched *60 Minutes* broadcast since December 16, 2012.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On December 1, 2013, the broadcast (delayed 50 minutes due to a Broncos–Kansas City Chiefs game) was watched by 18.09 million viewers, retaining 66% of its NFL lead-in (which earned 28.11 million viewers during the 7:00 p.m. hour).
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On March 25, 2018, the edition featuring Stormy Daniels giving details on her alleged affair with President Donald Trump drew 22.1 million viewers, the most since the 2008 Obama interview.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The broadcast was delayed due to the NCAA men's basketball regional final on CBS between Kansas and Duke going to overtime.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] As of June 26, 2017, *60 Minutes* had won a total of 138 Emmy Awards, a record for American primetime programs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The show received an Investigative Reporter and Editor medal for their segment "The Osprey", documenting a Marine cover-up of deadly flaws in the V-22 Osprey aircraft.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In 1983, a report by Morley Safer, "Lenell Geter's in Jail", helped exonerate a Texas man who was wrongly convicted and imprisoned for armed robbery.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] As of 2021, *60 Minutes* is the longest continuously running program of any genre scheduled during American network prime time.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays since December 7, 1975 (although since 2012, it moves to 7:30 p.m.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Eastern Time on Sundays if CBS has a late NFL game).
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The show has been praised for landmark journalism and received many awards.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On November 23, 1986, *60 Minutes* aired a segment greenlit by Hewitt, concerning the Audi 5000 automobile, a popular German luxury car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The story covered a supposed problem of "unintended acceleration" when the brake pedal was pushed, with emotional interviews with six people who sued Audi (unsuccessfully) after they crashed their cars, including one woman whose six-year-old son had been killed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In the *60 Minutes* segment footage was shown of an Audi 5000 with the accelerator "moving down on its own", accelerating the car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] It later emerged that an expert witness employed by one of the plaintiffs modified the accelerator with a concealed device, causing the "unintended acceleration".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Independent investigators concluded that this "unintended acceleration" was most likely due to driver error, where the driver let their foot slip off the brake and onto the accelerator.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Tests by Audi and independent journalists showed that even with the throttle wide open, the car would simply stall if the brakes were actually being used.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The incident devastated Audi sales in the United States, which did not rebound for 15 years.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The initial incidents which prompted the report were found by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and Transport Canada to have been attributable to operator error, where car owners had depressed the accelerator pedal instead of the brake pedal.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] CBS issued a partial retraction, without acknowledging the test results of involved government agencies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Years later, *Dateline NBC*, a rival to *60 Minutes*, was found guilty of similar tactics regarding the fuel tank integrity of General Motors pickup trucks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A segment aired in December, 1980, concerning the alleged Jeep CJ-5 *high rollover risk* as demonstrated in Insurance Institute for Highway Safety testing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The demonstration was a Jeep rolling over during an extreme turn at 20 mph (32 km/h), something that would not cause other cars to roll over.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] It was deemed by *60 Minutes* reporters as the "most dangerous thing on four wheels".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] After the show aired, many people were concerned about the safety of the vehicle, and following sales plummeted.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] This tarnished the reputation of the Jeep CJ; the model was discontinued in 1986.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Years after the incident occurred, it was found that the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety had attempted to roll the car 435 times, only having 8 rollovers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The show had also failed to mention/show that there were weights hanging on spots of the vehicle that had caused the vehicle to have a higher rollover risk.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In February 1989, *60 Minutes* aired a report by the Natural Resources Defense Council claiming that the use of daminozide (Alar) on apples presented an unacceptably high health risk to consumers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Apple sales dropped and CBS was sued unsuccessfully by apple growers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Alar was subsequently banned for use on food crops in the U.S. by the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA).
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On March 3, 1991, *60 Minutes* broadcast "Werner Erhard," which dealt with controversies involving Erhard's personal and business life.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A year after the *60 Minutes* piece aired, Erhard filed a lawsuit against CBS, claiming that the broadcast contained several "false, misleading and defamatory" statements about him.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] One month after filing the lawsuit, Erhard filed for dismissal.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Erhard later told Larry King in an interview that he dropped the suit after receiving legal advice telling him that in order to win it, he had to prove not only that CBS knew the allegations were false but also that CBS acted with malice.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In 1995, former Brown & Williamson Vice President for Research and Development Jeffrey Wigand provided information to *60 Minutes* producer Lowell Bergman pertaining to B&W having systematically hidden the health risks of their cigarettes .
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Furthermore, it was alleged that B&W had introduced foreign agents (such as fiberglass and ammonia) with the intent of enhancing the effect of nicotine.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Bergman began to produce a piece based upon the information, but ran into opposition from Don Hewitt who, along with CBS lawyers, feared a billion-dollar lawsuit from Brown and Williamson for tortious interference for encouraging Wigand to violate his non-disclosure agreement.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A number of people at CBS would benefit from a sale of CBS to Westinghouse Electric Corporation, including the head of CBS lawyers and CBS News.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Also, because of the interview, the son of CBS President Laurence Tisch (who also controlled Lorillard Tobacco) was among the people from the big tobacco companies at risk of being caught having committed perjury.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Due to Hewitt's hesitation, *The Wall Street Journal* instead broke Wigand's story.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The *60 Minutes* piece was eventually aired with substantially altered content and minus some of the most damning evidence against B&W.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The exposé of the incident was published in an article in *Vanity Fair* by Marie Brenner, entitled "The Man Who Knew Too Much".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In 1997, *60 Minutes* alleged that agents of the U.S.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Customs Service ignored drug trafficking across the Mexico–United States border at San Diego.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The only evidence was a memorandum apparently written by Rudy Camacho, who was the head of the San Diego branch office.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Based on this memo, CBS alleged that Camacho had allowed trucks belonging to a particular firm to cross the border unimpeded.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Mike Horner, a former Customs Service employee, had passed the memos on to *60 Minutes*, and even provided a copy with an official stamp.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Camacho was not consulted about the piece, and his career was devastated in the immediate term as his own department placed suspicion on him.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In the end, it turned out that Horner had forged the documents as an act of revenge for his treatment within the Customs Service.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Camacho sued CBS and settled for an undisclosed amount of money in damages.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* founder Don Hewitt was forced to issue an on-air retraction.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A legal battle between archaeologists and the Umatilla tribe over the remains of a skeleton, nicknamed Kennewick Man, was reported by *60 Minutes* on October 25, 1998, to which the Umatilla tribe reacted negatively.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The tribe considered the segment heavily biased in favor of the scientists, cutting out important arguments, such as explanations of the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The report focused heavily on the racial politics of the controversy and also added inflammatory arguments, such as questioning the legitimacy of Native American sovereignty—much of the racial focus of the segment was later reported to have been either unfounded and/or misinterpreted.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On March 12, 2000, *60 Minutes* aired an interview with Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] At the time, McVeigh had already been convicted and sentenced to death for the bombing of the Alfred P.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Murrah Federal Building in April 1995, and the subsequent deaths of 168 people.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On the program, McVeigh was given the opportunity to vent against the government.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Following the program, a federal policy called the Special Confinement Unit Media Policy was enacted prohibiting face-to-face interviews with death row inmates.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A federal inmate challenged the policy in *Hammer v.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit upheld the prison policy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In March 2010, the United States Supreme Court declined to hear an appeal in the case, and the policy limiting media access to death row inmates remains in place.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] CBS refuses to show the entire interview, and has stated no reasons.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The Killian documents controversy involved six documents critical of George W.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Bush's service in the Texas Air National Guard from 1972-73.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Four of these documents were presented as authentic in a *60 Minutes II* episode aired on September 8, 2004, less than two months before the 2004 presidential election, but it was later found that CBS had failed to authenticate the documents.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, several typewriter and typography experts concluded the documents are forgeries, as have some media sources.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] No forensic document examiners or typography experts authenticated the documents, which may not be possible without original documents.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Bill Burkett, claimed to have burned the originals after faxing copies to CBS.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The incident was dramatized for the feature-length film, *Truth*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On March 29, 2009, a segment titled "The Internet Is Infected" aired on *60 Minutes*, which featured an interview with Don Jackson, a data protection professional for SecureWorks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Jackson himself declared in the program that "a part of [his] job is to know the enemy".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] However, during the interview, Jackson showed a photo of Finnish upper-level comprehensive school pupils and misidentified them as Russian hackers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In the photo, one of the children wears a jacket with the coat of arms of Finland on it.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Another one wears a cap which clearly has the logo of Karjala, a Finnish brand of beer, on it.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The principal of the school in Taivalkoski confirmed that the photo was taken at the school about five years before the program was broadcast.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The photo's exact origins are unknown, but it is widely known in Finland, having been originally posted to the Finnish social networking site IRC-Galleria in the early 2000s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] It spread all over Finnish internet communities, and even originated a couple of patriotically titled (but intentionally misspelled) mock sites.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] *60 Minutes* later issued a correction and on-air apology.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] He also claimed to have visited a Benghazi hospital earlier that night where he saw Ambassador Christopher Stevens' body.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In the days following the report, Davies' personal actions were challenged.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The FBI, which had interviewed Davies several times and considered him a credible source, said the account Davies had given them was different from what he told *60 Minutes*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Davies stood by his story, but the inconsistency ultimately prompted *60 Minutes* to conclude it was a mistake to include Davies in their report.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] After the correction, a journalistic review was conducted by Al Ortiz, CBS News' executive director of standards and practices.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Ortiz determined that red flags about Davies' account were missed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Davies had told the program and written in his book that he told an alternative version of his actions to his employer, who he said had demanded that he stay inside his Benghazi villa as the attack unfolded.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] That alternative version was shared with U.S. authorities; *60 Minutes* was unable to prove the story Davies had told them was true.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Davies' book, *The Embassy House*, was published two days after the *60 Minutes* report, by Threshold Editions, part of the Simon and Schuster unit of CBS.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] It was pulled from shelves once *60 Minutes* issued its correction.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On November 26, 2013, Logan was forced to take a leave of absence due to the errors in the Benghazi report.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On December 15, 2013, *60 Minutes* aired a report on the workings of the National Security Agency (NSA) that was widely criticized as misleading and a biased "puff piece".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Complaints included that the Agency's perspective was presented unchallenged and that privacy campaigners were not invited to present the counter-arguments to the Agency's claims.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] These claims included NSA denials of "potentially extralegal" data collection.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The story was reported by John Miller, who once worked in the office of the Director of National Intelligence.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On March 30, 2014, *60 Minutes* presented a story on the Tesla Model S luxury electric automobile, with Scott Pelley conducting an interview with CEO Elon Musk concerning the car brand as well as his company SpaceX.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Within a day, the automotive blog site Jalopnik reported that the sounds accompanying footage of the car shown during the story were actually sounds from a traditional gasoline engine dubbed over the footage, when in reality the electric car makes no such sounds.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] CBS released a statement explaining that the sound was the result of an audio editing error, and subsequently removed the sound from the online version of the piece.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] However, several news outlets, as well as Jalopnik itself, expressed doubt over the authenticity of this explanation, noting the similar scandal involving Tesla Motors and the *New York Times* in 2013.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] After the resignation of CBS news head Les Moonves, an investigation into sexual harassment at CBS, including *60 Minutes*, uncovered evidence of long-running sexual harassment issues stemming from behavior of producers Jeff Fager and Don Hewitt.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Subsequently, Palm Beach County Mayor Dave Kerner accused *60 Minutes* of reporting "intentionally false" information, while Karol Markowicz of the *New York Post* characterized Alfonsi as coming off as a "political activist" in the segment.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] A spokesperson for *60 Minutes* defended the story for having included DeSantis' response to the accusation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] PolitiFact stated that by omitting DeSantis' remarks on why the state partnered with Publix to distribute vaccines, the clip could be considered to be "deceptive editing".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On May 16, 2021, Anderson Cooper's story in *60 Minutes* on the flaws in facial recognition technology used by the police resulting in incorrect identification of people of color received backlash for denying credit to the black female researchers who pioneered the field.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The segment was criticized by the Algorithmic Justice League for "deliberately excluding the groundbreaking and award-winning work of prominent black women AI researchers Joy Buolamwini, Dr.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Timnit Gebru, and Inioluwa Deborah Raji".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The segment was called out for its hypocrisy for failing to credit black women for their pioneering work in a segment highlighting how facial recognition software often leaves out black, Asian, and female faces.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] CBS later issued a statement explaining that these researchers were not included due to time restrictions of the segment.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On December 7, 2024, Donald Trump filed a $20 billion lawsuit against CBS and its parent company, Paramount Global, alleging that the network deceptively edited an interview with Vice President Kamala Harris on *60 Minutes* to sway public opinion in her favor.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] The lawsuit, submitted in the lead-up to the 2024 presidential election, claims that the editing distorted Harris's response regarding Middle East policy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Both parties agreed to enter mediation, coinciding with a planned $8 billion merger between Paramount and Skydance, which requires approval from the Federal Communications Commission (FCC).
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Within Paramount, there was reportedly internal disagreement over whether to settle the dispute, as the producers of *60 Minutes* maintained their conduct was appropriate and opposed offering an apology.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In early April 2025, Trump expressed his "hope" that the FCC would punish CBS for running on *60 Minutes* stories on Ukraine and Greenland that he disapproved of.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Trump filed a lawsuit in Texas accusing CBS of violating the state's Deceptive Trade Practices Act, a consumer protection law.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On April 22, 2025, Bill Owens resigned as the show's executive producer, telling staff he believed he no longer had journalistic independence.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] He said in a memo that the show would continue to cover the second Trump administration the same way it has covered others.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] In the "Last Minute" segment of the show on April 27, 2025, Scott Pelley praised Owens for ensuring that the types of controversial stories the show had covered since its creation, most recently the Gaza war and the Trump administration, were covered fairly.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On May 19, 2025, CBS News chief executive Wendy McMahon followed Bill Owens in resigning.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] McMahon explained in a memo to staff, “The past few months have been challenging.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On July 2, 2025, Paramount agreed to a $16 million settlement.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] As part of the deal, the company did not apologize or admit wrongdoing, agreed to release full transcripts of interviews with future U.S. presidential candidates after they air, and stated that the funds will go to Trump's future presidential library.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On the July 14, 2025, episode of CBS's late-night talk show *The Late Show with Stephen Colbert*, host Stephen Colbert called the settlement a "big fat bribe".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Three days later, CBS announced that it would not renew Colbert's contract with the network, and that it would end the *Late Show* franchise at the conclusion of the 2025–26 television season.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Although CBS claimed that the decision to end the show was "purely" financial, it was suspected that the decision may have been politically-motivated due to Colbert's comments and regular history of satirizing the Trump administration.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On December 21, 2025, CBS News abruptly pulled a planned segment on El Salvador's Terrorism Confinement Center (CECOT) and President Trump's deportation of Venezuelan migrants from that night's episode, and announced that it would be postponed to a future date.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Sharyn Alfonsi accused Bari Weiss—who had recently been named editor-in-chief of CBS News—of intervening for political reasons, despite the segment having been cleared by the network's staff.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On December 22, Canadian broadcaster Global accidentally made the original cut of the episode containing the CECOT story available on its video on demand platform, causing it to be widely disseminated online.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Alfonsi stated in a email memorandum to colleagues that the production team did request comments and interviews from White House officials, the State Department, and the Department of Homeland Security, which were all refused.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] On January 18, 2026, the segment aired alongside a piece on the relations between Minneapolis citizens and ICE officers after the death of Renée Good.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] Correspondent Scott Pelley was fired in June 2026.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p01] He complained about management, including CBS News Chief Bari Weiss, and the incoming executive-producer of the show, Nick Bilton.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The main *60 Minutes* show has created a number of spin-offs over the years.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In September 2004, the program was marred by controversy when it aired a report alleging that presidential candidate George W.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] Bush had previously been suspended from the Texas Air National Guard as unfit for duty; the claims were found to have been based on falsified documents received by the show's staff.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The show later moved to Friday nights in July 2005 (rebranding back to *60 Minutes II*), and aired its final episode on September 2, 2005.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In 2011, CNBC began airing a *60 Minutes* spin-off of its own, called *60 Minutes on CNBC*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] Hosted by Lesley Stahl and Steve Kroft, it aired updated business-related reports seen on the original broadcasts and offers footage that was not included when the segments first aired.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In 2013, CBS's sister premium television network Showtime premiered *60 Minutes Sports*, a monthly spin-off focused on sports-related stories and classic interviews from the show's archives.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] Personalities from CBS Sports also contributed to the program; correspondents included Sharyn Alfonsi and Armen Keteyian.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The spin-off was considered a competitor to HBO's *Real Sports*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In June 2020, the show launched *60 in 6* on Quibi, featuring original weekly 6-minute programs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] Correspondents were Enrique Acevedo, Seth Doane, Wesley Lowery, and Laurie Segall.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] It was originally set to launch in April 2020.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] On the June 21, 2020, broadcast of *60 in 6*, Doane covered the show's exposure to COVID-19 in a piece titled "CBS News Battles COVID-19".
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The piece revealed that CBS News had flown in staffers, including from Seattle and Rome, in early March 2020 to begin filming promotional material for *60 in 6*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] This brought COVID-19-positive people in close contact with CBS employees; as a result, CBS Broadcast Center and several other buildings in Manhattan were temporarily closed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] Quibi went bankrupt in December 2020 and the program concluded with it.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In March 2021, Paramount+ premiered *60 Minutes+*, a weekly spin-off aimed at a younger audience.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The correspondents from *60 in 6* returned for this spin-off, as well as producer Jonathan Blakely.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In January 2022, the show was cancelled after 30 episodes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] For the *60 Minutes* 25th anniversary program in 1993, Charles Kuralt revisited notable stories and celebrity appearances and also interviewed Don Hewitt and correspondents, both the active and some former ones.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The Australian version of *60 Minutes* premiered on February 11, 1979.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] It still airs each Sunday night at 7:30 p.m. on the Nine Network and affiliates.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] Although Nine Network has the rights to the format, as of 2007, it does not have rights to stories from the American program, which is owned by competitor 10 News Australia after Network Ten's acquisition by CBS in 2017.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] Nevertheless, stories from the flagship *60 Minutes* program in the U.S. often air on the Australian program by subleasing them from Ten.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In 1981, *60 Minutes* won a Logie Award for their investigation of lethal abuses at the Chelmsford psychiatric hospital in Sydney.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In the mid-1980s, an edited version (approx.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] This version retained the English-language track of the original but also featured German dubbing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The New Zealand version of *60 Minutes* has aired on national television since 1989, when it was originally launched on TV3.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the rights were acquired by TVNZ, who began broadcasting it in 1993.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The network aired the program for nine years before dropping it in 2002 for its own program, entitled *Sunday*, which is currently the highest-rated current affairs show broadcast on New Zealand television, followed by *20/20*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] *60 Minutes* was broadcast by rival network TV3, before switching to the Sky Television owned Prime channel in 2013, when the contract changed hands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] In 1992, the GNT channel brought its original version with dubbed subtitles from that country.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] And later, in 2004, Rede Bandeirantes, planned a licensed localized version, but the plan was cancelled.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] And even so that year, it returned as a frame, i.e. a rubric in the program *Domingo Espetacular* on Rede Record, a competitor of Rede Globo's program *Fantástico*.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] SIC Notícias acquired the broadcasting rights to the program in 2001.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The original episodes were shown in Portugal with introductory and final comments by journalist Mário Crespo, who conducted the program until 2014.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] It is presently hosted by anchors of the aforementioned network on a rotational basis, who eventually adopted the previous model.
[src:american-motors-corporation/60-minutes-p02] The news program of National Broadcasting of Chile (TVN), the public television network in that country, was named *60 Minutos* ("60 Minutes") from 1975 to 1988, but the program had no association with the American version and no investigative reporting.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit was born to poor parents in Jersey City, New Jersey.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] He was briefly the secretary for the purchasing agent at the Chalmers-Detroit Motor Company.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] He began his career with Hudson in 1910, by joining the firm's purchasing department, less than six months after the production of the company's first automobile.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] He was a stenographer, and had no flair for market analysis, product development, or design.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit was named president and CEO of Hudson following the death of the corporation's founding president and CEO Roy D.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Using lines of credit arranged for Chapin before his death, Barit helped to steer Hudson back toward profitability in the late 1930s.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] In 1938, Barit proposed a plan to reduce used-car inventories as a method to stimulate not only the national economy, but also help employment and sales in the automobile industry.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Sales of Hudson rebounded through the economic recession of 1938.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Marking the 30th anniversary of the founding of the company in 1939, Barit kept up an optimistic business view by highlighting Hudson's opportunities.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] However, the domestic automobile industry was fiercely competitive with many once-famous firms such as Hupmobile, Chandler, Peerless, Winton, and Pierce-Arrow going bankrupt and Hudson facing a similar fate as it posted a loss of $1.5 million in 1940.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] The company shifted quickly for World War II production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Hudson made antiaircraft guns, engines for landing barges, and aircraft parts netting an average of nearly $2 million a year during the war.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] After the war, Barit wanted Hudson to be a leader among the independent domestic motormakers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] In 1945, Barit successfully fought off a below-market rate tender offer for Hudson Motors by the Fisher family—founders of General Motors Fisher Body division.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Under Barit's leadership, Hudson was one of the first automakers to convert to civilian production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Production for 1946 totaled 93,000 or nearly 6,000 more than it made in 1940.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Hudson increased production in 1947 to 103,000.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] This allowed Hudson to double its profit to $5.7 million in 1947 compared to the previous year.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit wanted Hudson to build on the automobile industry's long list of "firsts" (e.g., the first aluminum pistons, the first rear luggage compartment, the first steering-wheel gearshift).
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] The conservative Barit gave the go-ahead for Hudson's step-down body design—a revolutionary design that catapulted the firm to the forefront of automotive body engineering in the postwar market.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit invested $18 million to retool for the new design.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] When combined with the firm's Twin-H straight-6, Hudson's corporate-sponsored race teams, headed by Marshall Teague, dominated the NASCAR circuit from 1951 through 1954.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] In the early 1950s, instead of reshaping Hudson's aging step-down design, or investing in V8 engine technology, Barit guided the company toward developing a compact car that Hudson could market.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] He "meddled" in the development and design of the company's products, failing to capitalize on the expertise of the firm's professionals in those areas.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Moran fancied the 1952 Ford's wrap-around rear window and roofline, thus influenced Barit to introduce a similar design for the new car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] The final result was that the car's styling closely mimicked the larger 1952-1954 Ford in many respects which emerged as the antithesis of the low-slung step-down bodies.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] The new compact car, named the Hudson Jet, did not attract buyers, and the expense of its development (and failure) combined with Hudson's lack of resources to update their senior line of cars spelled the end for the company.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Hudson Motors was subsequently acquired through a friendly merger by Nash Motors in 1954, creating American Motors Corporation (AMC).
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit served on the board of AMC until 1956 when he resigned in protest over the likelihood that Hudson would be phased out of production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit felt that his trust in AMC had been betrayed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Romney, AMC's president, felt that Hudson and Nash were no longer relevant players in the automotive market and retired both names at the end of the 1957 model year production to make way for the new Rambler brand.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] For personal use, Barit had a 1951 Hudson modified by the Derham Body Company to a limousine that was later updated to Hudson's 1953 front-end treatment.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] This car is now part of the collections at The Henry Ford.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] According to his son, Robert Barit, the last car that A.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit owned was a Hudson, and after it was retired, he refused to own any other automobile brand.
[src:american-motors-corporation/a-e-barit] Barit died at his home in Grosse Pointe Park, Michigan, on July 14, 1974.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] The **AMC Model 20** is an automotive axle manufactured by American Motors Corporation (AMC) and AM General.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] The AMC 20 is a carrier-tube axle, which is where the axle tubes press into the housing, and the cover is bolted to the rear.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] They have an 8+7⁄8-inch (230 mm) ring gear and use a 29 spline axle shaft.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] The differential cover is round with twelve bolts, making it one of the easiest axles to identify.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] Most AMC 30 rear axles use a 3-inch (76 mm) tube, and the gasket shape is round with almost the same height and width (10+1⁄32 in (255 mm) x 10+25⁄64 in (264 mm).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] The AMC 20 was most often used with V8 engines in cars with rear-wheel-drive.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] This axle has an extensive history of use in drag racing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] It is also found in Jeeps for the rear and was also used in the AM General Humvee.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] The AMC 20 rear axle used in Jeep CJ applications with two-piece axle shafts was described as having a weak and flexible housing, while the version used in full-sized Jeeps (Wagoneer, Gladiator, and M-715) is stronger but does not have as much aftermarket support as other brands.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] There were many ratios offered over the lifetime of the AMC 20.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] A letter code stamped on a small pad at the right side of the center housing or carrier flange indicates installed gears.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] AMC changed or reused letter codes during the axle's long life.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] While the codes can be helpful, the axle ratio could have been changed after the vehicle was produced.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-20] Dealer installed gears (3.73, 4.10, 4.44:1, and 5.00) were available There are other gear ratios available in the aftermarket.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The **AMC AMX-GT** is a concept car that was developed by American Motors Corporation (AMC) for the 1968 show car circuit.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The design of the grand touring-type rear-wheel-drive pillarless coupe of monocoque construction with two doors and a truncated rear end treatment was influenced by AMC stylist Dick Teague.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The AMX GT was built by shortening the 4-seat Javelin coupé to a 97-inch (2,464 mm) wheelbase (the same as the production 2-seat AMXs), lowering, or "chopping", the roof and cutting off the tail.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] At the New York International Auto Show in April 1968 it was red with a white stripe on the sides that ran across the roof.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] It also had plain, flush wheel covers, generic all-black tires, a side-mounted exhaust, a ram-air intake hood, integrated roof spoiler and fixed rear side windows (quarter glass) with no support (or "B") pillar.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The wheels were soon replaced by an alloy five-spoke design with Goodyear white-letter tires.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The hood and roof were repainted a contrasting dark blue.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] This color scheme, which followed the major character lines of the car, was applied to some of the early factory-sponsored race cars before AMC changed to bands of red, white, and blue.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The AMX GT provided several clues to future production models and options.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The most immediately available were the optional side exhaust pipes for 1969 Javelins and AMXs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] A slightly modified version of the show car's hood scoop became part of the factory production "Go package" option on Javelins and AMXs for the 1970 model year.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The flat black "shadow mask" paint treatment also became available on the 1970 AMXs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The AMX GT's truncated tail treatment reappeared in 1970 on the Gremlin subcompact.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The show car provided the general shape for the small Gremlin.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] The design, an example of Teague's approach to maximizing AMC's limited resources, resulted in a new version from an existing platform.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] In AMC's 1969 annual report to shareholders, various AMX GT design drawings and proposals served as the background for pictures of top AMC executives.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx-gt] For the official photograph of the board of directors, the members posed with the second version of the concept car, this time with its hood and roof painted black.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The **AMC AMX** is a two-seat GT-style muscle car produced by American Motors Corporation from 1968 through 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] As one of just two American-built two-seaters, the AMX was in direct competition with the one-inch (2.5 cm) longer wheelbase Chevrolet Corvette, for substantially less money.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It was based on the new-for-1968 Javelin, but with a shorter wheelbase and deletion of the rear seat.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In addition, the AMX's rear quarter windows remained fixed, making it a coupe, while the Javelin was a true two-door hardtop.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Fitted with the standard high-compression 290 cu in (4.8 L) or optional 343 cu in (5.6 L) or 390 cu in (6.4 L) AMC V8 engine, the AMX offered sporty performance at an affordable price.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Despite this value and enthusiastic initial reception by automotive media and enthusiasts, sales never thrived.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] However, the automaker's larger objectives to refocus AMC's image on performance and to bring younger customers into its dealer showrooms were achieved.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] After three model years, the two-seat version was discontinued.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX's signature badging was transferred to a high-performance version of its four-seat sibling, the Javelin, from the 1971 to 1974 model years.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors capitalized on the respected reputation of the original two-seat AMXs by reviving the model designation for performance-equipped coupe versions of the compact Hornet in 1977, Concord in 1978, and the subcompact Spirit in 1979 and 1980.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX name originates from the "*A*merican *M*otors e*x*perimental" code used on a concept vehicle and then on two prototypes shown on the company's "Project IV" automobile show tour in 1966.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] One was a fiberglass two-seat "AMX", and the other was a four-seat "AMX II".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] These radically styled offerings reflected the company's strategy to shed its "economy car" image and appeal to a more youthful, performance-oriented market.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The original AMX full-scale models were developed in 1965 by AMC's advanced styling studios under the direction of Charles Mashigan.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The two-seat AMX was a "big hit on the auto show circuit in 1966" and featured a rumble seat that opened out from the rear decklid for extra passengers called a "Ramble" seat.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] AMC executives saw the opportunity to change consumers' perceptions of the automaker from Romney's economy car image to the realities of the new marketplace interested in sporty, performance-oriented vehicles.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Evans requested a car like the AMX to be put into production quickly.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Two simultaneous development programs emerged for a production car: a modified Javelin and another for a completely new vehicle bodied in fiberglass.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The first approach was selected to allow AMC to use its existing technology and unibody manufacturing expertise to make relatively inexpensive modifications to the Javelin, approximating the prototype's styling and proportions.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The automaker could turn out steel bodies in large numbers, so it rejected developing plastic (or fiberglass) bodies because those are intended only for low-production models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The first fully operational unit debuted as part of AMC's AMX project in 1966.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The once-"frumpy" automaker jumped on the "pony car bandwagon" with its "attractive Javelin" and soon introduced the "unique" AMX featuring a design where "hoods didn't come any longer, nor decks any shorter".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Vic Raviolo, previously responsible for the Lincolns that raced in the Carrera Panamericana during the 1950s, was involved with engineering AMC's new sports-car-type coupe.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX was the first steel-bodied, two-seat American performance car since the 1955 through 1957 Ford Thunderbird.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Ford's original two-seater evolved into a four-seat personal luxury car starting in 1958.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX was also the only mass-produced, domestic two-seater to share the market with Chevrolet's Corvette since the 1957 Thunderbird.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] With a short, 97 in (2,464 mm), wheelbase, the AMX's direct competition was the one-inch longer (98 in (2,489 mm) Chevrolet Corvette.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX's manufacturer's suggested retail price (MSRP) was US$3,245 (US$30,043 in 2025 dollars ), nearly 25% below and over $1,000 less than the Corvette's price tag.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX was introduced to the press at the Daytona International Speedway on 15 February 1968, just over four months after the Javelin went on sale.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In the demonstrations on the race track, the new AMXs ran at speeds up to 130 mph (209 km/h).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors' group vice president, Vic Raviolo, described the AMX as "the Walter Mitty Ferrari".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] To promote the new car, AMC's manager for performance activities, Carl Chakmakian, asked world land speed record holder Craig Breedlove to put the AMX through its paces before the new vehicles were even available for sale.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In January 1968, two specially prepared AMXs set 106 world speed and endurance records at Goodyear's track in Texas driven by Breedlove, his wife Lee, and Ron Dykes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Breedlove's "Spirit of America" crew and Traco Engineering had six weeks to prepare the cars before they were to be displayed at the Chicago Auto Show in February.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMC V8 engines, such as the 290 cu in (4.8 L) engine in one car was bored out to 304 cu in (5.0 L) and the 390 cu in (6.4 L) in the other to 397 cu in (6.5 L).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The shop installed exhaust headers, eight-quart oil pans, oil coolers, hi-rise intake manifolds, racing camshafts with solid lifters and stronger springs, and larger carburetors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The cars had engine and rear-end oil coolers, as well as 37 US gal (140 L; 31 imp gal) cell-type safety fuel tanks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Engine components were X-rayed and Magnafluxed to check for cracks, as were chassis components.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Chassis preparation included heavy-duty front and rear springs (part of the factory's optional handling package), rear spring traction control arms, heavy-duty shock absorbers, and a "panhard" type track bar in the rear to eliminate side sway.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Wide magnesium racing wheels and Goodyear racing tires replaced the stock road wheels and standard tires.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The cars were aerodynamically modified: the front ends were lowered, the hoods were slanted down, and spoilers were installed below the front bumpers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The car interiors had structure-stiffening roll cages for driver protection, a stock bucket seat modified for additional support, and supplementary engine-monitoring instruments.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Breedlove also took the AMX to Bonneville reaching 189 mph (304 km/h) in a United States Auto Club (USAC) sanctioned run, as well as an unofficial run of over 200 mph (322 km/h).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX was not only sporty and attractive, but it introduced many industry firsts.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The American Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) named the AMX as the "best-engineered car of the year" in 1969 and 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The 1968 models also included an innovative fiberglass safety padding, a "plastic" on the inside of the windshield posts that was first used on the AMC Javelins.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] For the following year's award, the SAE recognition included the 1970 AMXs (and Javelins) being the first production cars to use windshields that were safer, thinner, and lighter than ordinary laminated glass.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Developed by Corning, the glass featured a chemically hardened layer designed to give under impact and crumble into small granules to reduce injuries.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors also incorporated new designs for windshield sealing for the 1970 models and developed a systems solutions process that began in the styling studio to ensure maximum efficiency.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors promoted the mid-model year launch of the AMX to automotive journalists at Daytona to emphasize its sports car performance, as well as with a marketing agreement with Playboy Enterprises.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] To introduce the AMX to its dealers, AMC held meetings at nine Playboy Clubs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX was introduced to the public on 24 February 1968, five months after the Javelin and other 1968 AMC cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX was promoted as "the only American sports car that costs less than $3500".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The two-seat AMX was "meant for a small, well-defined market niche, and it pulled young people into AMC dealer showrooms in never before seen numbers".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Numerous road tests described the new AMX as a "handsome two-seater with American-style acceleration and European-style handling".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] All AMXs came with four-barrel carbureted small block AMC V8 engines in several versions: 290 cu in (4.8 L) (225 hp (168 kW), N-code), 343 cu in (5.6 L) (290 hp (220 kW), T-code), as well as the 390 cu in (6.4 L) "AMX" featuring 315 hp (235 kW) with 425 pound force-feet (576 N⋅m) of torque (X-code).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] All are derived from the same external size block.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A BorgWarner T-10 four-speed manual transmission was standard, as were unique traction bars, dual exhaust system, and fatter tires for better traction.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A "Shift-Command" three-speed automatic transmission with the capability of manual shifting (BorgWarner model M-11B or M-12) was optional together with a floor console mounted shifter.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A popular "Go-Package" option was available with the four-barrel 343 or 390 engine.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It included power-assisted front disk brakes, "Twin-Grip" differential, E70x14 red-stripe performance tires on 6-inch wide steel road wheels, heavy-duty suspension with thicker sway-bars, heavy-duty cooling, as well as other performance enhancements.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A wide range of specialized performance parts were also available through AMC dealers for installation on customer's cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] These were known as "Group 19" parts because of how AMC organized its parts books.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] According to several sources, "Breedlove Replica" cars to commemorate the speed and endurance records were offered by AMC.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The *Standard Catalog of American Muscle Cars 1960–1972* describes an estimated 50 "Breedlove" AMXs were sold featuring the red, white, and blue paint scheme along with the standard 4-barrel 290 cu in (4.8 L) V8 with four-speed manual transmission.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Some sources describe other AMXs as having been painted Playmate Pink at the factory.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] AMC's marketing vice-president, Bill McNealy, who handed over the keys to Angela Dorian's car, mentioned that "a number of them" were finished in pink.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In late 1968, a Playmate Pink AMX was special-ordered by a dealership in rural Potosi, Missouri.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] This 1969 model year car's door tag indicates a "00" paint code (meaning a special-order color).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It has a 390 V8 with automatic transmission, as well as the performance "GO" Package, air conditioning, and leather seats.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In the late-1960s, The Hertz Corporation offered "rent-a-racer" program in selected locations that included cars such as Corvettes, Jaguar XK-Es, Shelby Mustangs, and AMXs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] There is no record of how many AMXs were ordered by Hertz for their fleet.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Still, the factory "Build Sheet" for a car may indicate that AMC sold the car to Hertz.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Thoroughbred Motors in Denver, Colorado, modified an estimated 22 new AMXs for select AMC dealerships to have ready-made racers for both the dragstrips and road courses nearby.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] They were named "Von Piranha" and the changes included the addition of two sets of air scoops on each C-pillar with ducts to cool the rear brakes and on the roof above the windshield that was reportedly functional to cool the cockpit on race-bred versions.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX's twin hood bulges were cut open to increase airflow in the engine bay.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The original Piranha buildup was believed to have AMC's Group 19 R4B intake stamped with the Von Piranha logo and a 950 CFM Holley three-barrel carburetor.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The sales manager at Thoroughbred at the time and local racing legend, Ronald Hunter, raced a Piranha at the Continental Divide Raceways and other events.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX's full second model year saw only slight changes, except for a $52 increase in its base price.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The five-spoke Magnum 500 steel road wheels were no longer chrome plated, but now came with a stainless steel trim ring.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The racing stripes were now available in five colors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The interior featured a revised instrumentation with the 0–8000 rpm tachometer moved to match the speedometer that was now calibrated to 140 mph (230 km/h).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Interior door panels were revised, carpeting was upgraded, new leather upholstery was optional, and the gas pedal became suspended.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Later production cars received a hood over the instruments in front of the driver.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Trunk capacity was 9.7 cubic feet (275 L).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Starting in January 1969, all manual transmission AMXs came with a Hurst floor shifter.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The center console-mounted three-speed "Shift-Command" automatic remained optional with "1", "2", and "D" forward settings.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The "D" mode was for fully automatic operation, but the driver could shift manually through all three gears by starting in the "1" setting for first gear with no upshift, then the "2" setting for second gear with no upshift, and finally to third-gear in the "D" setting.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A "Big Bad" paint option for $34 became available in mid-1969.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The neon brilliant blue (BBB), orange (BBO), and green (BBG) exteriors included color-matched front and rear bumpers, as well as a unique slim bright lower grille moulding for the front bumper and two vertical rubber-faced painted bumper guards for the rear.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The factory-painted 1969 AMXs were 195 in BBB, 285 in BBO, and 283 in BBG.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The "California 500 Special" is a version of 1969 AMXs sold only by Southern California American Motors Dealer Association members.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It was part of a marketing campaign to commemorate the 1969 season at the Riverside International Raceway.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] They would serve as pace car and the dealers would sell replicas.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] All were finished in Big Bad Green with black stripes and included the 390 Go-Pac, automatic transmission, air conditioning, power steering, adjustable steering wheel, tinted windows, radio, light group, visibility group, and a saddle leather interior.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The cars also featured "Trendsetter Sidewinder" exhaust side pipes in place of the molding strips on the rocker panels and were identified by brass plaques mounted on the hood blisters that had crossed checkered racing flags and the words 500 Special.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A total of 283 AMXs were built in Big Bad Green for the 1969 model year; however, the exact number of California 500 Special versions is unknown, with only an estimate of 32.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] AMC also introduced the Super Stock AMX.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] To maximize quarter-mile performance, the 390 engine was equipped with twin Holley carburetors and 12.3:1 compression-ratio cylinder heads, plus aftermarket *Doug's* headers and exhaust system, and the tires were drag slicks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Hurst Performance carried out several additional modifications.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors rated the car at 340 hp (250 kW), but the National Hot Rod Association (NHRA) rated it at 420 horsepower (310 kW) and shuffled it among various competition classes that included SS/G and SS/D.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The Super Stock AMXs were also put in SS/E class by NHRA based on the car's 3,050 lb (1,383 kg) weight and estimated 405 hp (302 kW) and ultimately slotted into the SS/C class.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Most of the cars were prepared and custom-painted by AMC dealers to be campaigned at big racing events where they ran in the low 11s on the tracks.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The best recorded quarter-mile was 10.73 seconds at 128 mph (206 km/h).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The Super Stock AMX was meant for the race track and lacked comfort equipment such as a heater.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The car could be ordered in all white or vertical bands of red, white, and blue, distinguishing numerous AMC competition cars of the day.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The base price was $5,994, approximately $1,900 more than a fully loaded 1969 AMX.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Moreover, the factory warranty was unavailable for these cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The Pikes Peak International Hill Climb used 1969 AMXs as pace cars for the hillclimb race to the summit of Pikes Peak that was held on 29 June 1969 in Colorado.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX Pace and Courtesy cars were used by racers (including Bobby Unser) to practice the week before the race up the mountain.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] There were 12 (10 according to some sources) pace/courtesy AMXs, and all were equipped with the "390 Go-Pac" option and finished in "Frost White" with red stripes and red interiors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Many AMC and Jeep vehicles have participated in the annual race, winning class titles and setting records.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] However, the only two-seat AMX officially raced in the hill climb was a 1969 model by Larry G.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The original AMX's "Ramble" seat idea was considered for possible production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A working prototype was built in 1968 from a regular AMX by James Jeffords, a designer-customizer, and was named the AMX-R.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Jeffords was also head of the Javelin Trans Am Racing Team for AMC.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Together with industrial designer Brooks Stevens, they decided to also "plush up" the interior, add custom paint treatment and hood with Jeffords's name in badge form, as well as a modified suspension as part of their plan to offer an optional Ramble seat for 500 production cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The prototype was prepared by Dave Puhl's House of Kustoms in Palatine, Illinois.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] However, numerous problems prevented serial production, including safety and product liability concerns, AMC's refusal to sell him the cars to modify, as well as the adverse reaction from Ralph Nader to the exposed exterior seating idea.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX-R's special blacked-out hood treatment would later be offered as a "shadow mask" option on 1970 AMX models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors 1970 AMX advertising headlined, "We made the AMX look tougher this year because it's tougher this year".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] They were mildly facelifted resembling the first two model years, but the changes were different enough to be a separate design for 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Featured was a new front-end design with a longer hood that had a "power blister" with two large openings.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] These air intakes were functional cold ram-air induction system with the popular "Go Package" available with the 360 and 390 engines.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The new grille was flush and full-width, incorporating the headlamps.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The revised rear end also featured full-width taillamps and a single center-mounted backup light.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Side marker lights were now shared with several other AMC models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Riding on the same wheelbase 97-inch (2,464 mm) as before, the changes increased the AMX's overall body length by about 2 in (50.8 mm) to 179 in (4,547 mm).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors also changed the AMX's engine lineup for 1970 with the introduction of a new 360 cu in (5.9 L) four-barrel (290 hp (220 kW), P-code) to replace the 343 cu in (5.6 L) V8.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The smallest 290 was dropped, and AMC could claim 65 more base horsepower than the AMXs featured previously.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The 390 cu in (6.4 L) V8 engine continued, but upgraded to new heads with 51 cc (3.1 cu in) combustion chambers that increased power to 325 hp (330 PS; 242 kW) at 4800 rpm and 430 lb⋅ft (583 N⋅m) of torque at 3200 rpm.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The code remained "X" for the engine on the vehicle identification number (VIN).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The "Go package" was available with the 360 cu in (5.9 L) engine (including power front disc brakes, F70x14 raised white letter tires, handling package, heavy-duty cooling, and the ram-air induction system) for $298.85, or including the 390 engine for $383.90.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Also new, the front double wishbone suspension had ball joints, upper and lower control arms, coil springs, and shock absorbers above the upper control arms; as well as trailing struts on the lower control arms.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The "Magnum 500" road wheels were now standard, but the new "Machine" 15x7 inch slot-styled wheels became a mid-year option.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The interiors of the AMX were also redesigned.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The broad wood-grained dashboard, center console, and two-spoke "Rim Blow" steering wheel were new.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Tall bucket seats now featured a "clamshell design" integrating the headrests.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The exterior rearview mirror featured a new design that sometimes matched the car's body color.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The three "Big Bad" exterior paints continued to be optional on the 1970 AMXs, but they now came with regular chrome bumpers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A new "shadow mask" exterior finish applied over any available AMX color was a $52 option, which included a satin black-painted hood, engine compartment, front fender tops, and side window surrounds offset by thin silver striping.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] As an American-built two-seater, the AMC AMX was a high-performance car with few equals.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] They were campaigned with factory support and by independents in a variety of road and track racing series as well as being classified as grand tourers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The cars were regular performers on dragstrips across the United States.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Drivers included Shirley Shahan, better known as the "Drag-On Lady", and Lou Downy.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] National Hot Rod Association (NHRA) champion Wally Booth raced AMXs in both the Super Stock and the Pro Stock classes.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The 1968 and 1969 AMXs with AMC's 390 cu in (6.4 L) engines compete in contemporary Nostalgia Super Stock drag racing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Owners have also modified AMXs to compete in modern Pro Touring car racing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The Sports Car Club of America (SCCA) classed the AMX in B Production for amateur competition, the same class as the Shelby GT350.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] An AMX scored second place in the 1969 SCCA national championship.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The two-seat AMX was never eligible for SCCA Trans-Am competition.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A 1969 AMX was entered in the 1971 and 1972 Cannonball Baker Sea-to-Shining-Sea Memorial Trophy Dash, an unofficial automobile race from New York City and Darien, CT, on the US Atlantic (east) coast, to Redondo Beach, a Los Angeles suburb on the Pacific (west) coast.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A team of enthusiastic brothers, Tom and Ed Bruerton, finished the 1971 competition in fifth place.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] They drove 2,897 miles (4,662 km) in 37 hours and 48 minutes at an average of 77.3 mph (124 km/h), with no speeding tickets.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Their AMX already had 90,000 miles (144,841 km) on the odometer and the brothers had previously taken it on numerous endurance rides, including "a rocky ride the entire length of the Baja California Peninsula." They again entered "their battlescarred AMX one more time" in the 1972 run.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The brothers finished in eighth place, making the coast-to-coast outlaw race in 39 hours and 42 minutes at an average of 72.3 mph (116 km/h).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The two-seat AMX was built for three model years following its debut as a mid-year model on 15 February 1968.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The first 1968 model year cars were scheduled to appear in dealer showrooms on 19 March 1968.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In 1969, American Motors showed the next generation AMX/2 concept car in the automobile show circuit.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] As the two-seater AMX production ceased in 1970, AMC was developing a sophisticated European-engineered alternative, the AMX/3 for 1971 introduction.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A total of 24 right-hand drive 1969 model-year AMXs were hand-assembled under license in Australia by Australian Motor Industries (AMI) between August 1969 and July 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] They used the name **Rambler AMX** as AMI produced the Rambler range of cars since October 1960.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Complete knock down (CKD) kits were shipped from Kenosha, Wisconsin to AMI's facilities at Port Melbourne in Victoria.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Only three colors were offered: White, Safety Wattle Yellow, and Signal Red.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Differences to the RHD Australian AMXs (compared to the U.S. models) included different outside rear-view mirrors and black vinyl trim inside the "AMX" circle logo on the C-pillars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] As with other Australian-assembled AMC models built in right-hand drive, windscreen wipers were not reversed, remaining LHD pattern, but the power brake booster and heater on the firewall were swapped over.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Although the power steering pump remained in its usual left location, the remainder of the steering components were on the right side of the car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The cars came with 343 cu in (5.6 L) and automatic transmission, power steering, power disk brakes, "twin-grip" rear axle, and other items that were optional on the U.S. models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] All Australian AMX interiors were finished in black and featured unique seats, door panels, and a fiberglass RHD dashboard with a wood-grained instrument cluster in front of the driver.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The Australian AMXs came with a significant level of equipment and were promoted as "personal super cars".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A concept car with a folding exposed rear seat was introduced by AMC at the 1966 Society of Automotive Engineers convention in Detroit.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] This was the first "AMX" (American Motors Experimental) named car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The sports car design features a rumble seat for two additional passengers that was described as a "Ramble Seat" in homage to the automaker's predecessor Rambler models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] This back seat folds into the trunk space, and the rear window flips down, but these are not fully weatherproof designs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The roof design also has no "A" pillars, providing greater visibility.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The fiberglass-bodied "pushmobile" concept has no interior, engine, drivetrain, or suspension.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The concept was widely covered by the automotive media and the car featured on several auto magazine covers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It was painted orange or metallic blue to be shown on the auto show circuit.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It received positive reviews that convinced management to put the car into production.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] This 1966 AMX also gave rise to several other AMX show cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A fiberglass-bodied AMX I concept car was made in 1966 to be part of AMC's "Project IV" exhibit.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Built by Smith Inland of Ionia, Michigan, one of the two fiberglass-bodied concept cars was reportedly destroyed in a crash test convincing AMC's engineers and designers to use a traditional steel body.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The remaining domestic-built fiberglass prototype features round headlamps.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors' president Roy Abernethy sanctioned the Turin coachbuilder Vignale to construct an operational car in steel.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It was a hand-built show car using a modified 1966 Rambler American chassis on a 98 in (2,489 mm) wheelbase powered by a 290 cu in (4.8 L) V8 engine.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Delivered in 78 days and known as the "AMX Vignale", it was first displayed at the 1966 New York International Auto Show.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The Vignale car features a "split-vee" windshield.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] This cantilever-type roof incorporates a built-in concealed roll bar, rectangular European-type headlamps, and a custom interior with full bucket seats flanking an aircraft-type console.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The fully functional "Ramble-Seat" was operated by a push-button from inside the car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Vince Gardner, an outside consultant, designed the fiberglass-bodied AMX II, a less radical two-door for the "Project IV" exhibit.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] This four-passenger hardtop (no B-pillar) notchback coupe had little in common with the AMX I.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] This car featured a longer wheelbase and an overall length of 187 in (4,750 mm).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The windshield wiper blades were concealed by a panel that raises when wipers are activated.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The grille that was surrounded by a massive bumper had horizontal multi-bars with hidden headlamps.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Safety innovations included doors that locked automatically when the engine was started, reflectors on the sides of the rear fenders, rear tail lamps that signaled the driver's intentions: green when the car is in motion, amber when the driver removes foot from the accelerator, and red when braking.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Developed for the 1968 auto show circuit, the AMX GT is a concept car based on a shortened and "chopped" Javelin with a Kammback rear end.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX GT show car provided design clues to future production models and performance options.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In the late 1960s, George Barris made bolt-on customizing kits for the AMX that were marketed through AMC dealers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Changing customer preferences meant that traditional car customization was being replaced by quick bolt-on accessory personalization.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Barris joined this trend by offering a variety of spoiler, body additions, and wheel options.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors requested Barris to provide enhancements for the Javelins and the AMX.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Available through AMC dealers as complete kits or as separate items.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The package included a performance hood, rear spoiler, grille, racing side mirrors, and unique wheels.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Barris also performed a radical custom treatment on a 1969 AMX.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The car was built for the second season of episodes of the *Banacek* detective television series.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] It was a true custom for that time, and working with Joe Bailon, the car was lowered, and its body was heavily modified.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Its roof was cut down almost 5 in (127 mm) and the car was lengthened by 18 in (457 mm).
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Featuring a sculpted body with louvered accents, it became known as the AMX-400.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The car featured a taillight system that glowed green during acceleration, amber during deceleration, and red during braking.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A third-generation AMX concept car, the AMX/3, debuted at the February 1970 Chicago Auto Show.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Engine-less and fashioned in fiberglass, the original AMX/3 prototype was a "push-mobile" show car only.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Introduced in Rome in March 1970, the functional steel prototype was constructed by Giotto Bizzarrini, Salvatore Diomante, and Giorgetto Giugiaro of Italdesign.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors placed an order for 30 operational cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX/3 body mold was sent to Italian grand tourer maker Giotto Bizzarrini, whose Turin facility hand made driveable mid-engined, steel-bodied cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Built on a 105.3 in (2,675 mm) wheelbase, the Bizzarrini prototypes used the AMC 390 cu in (6.4 L) V8 and an Italian OTO Melara four-speed transaxle.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX/3 is considered one of Bizzarrini's car-masterpieces.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The steel Italian cars differed from the original AMC design in having fewer but functional rear decklid louvers, louvered hoods, and, in some cases, hood scoops to direct fresh air into the heating-A/C system.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Further engineering improvements and road testing was done by BMW, which declared the AMX/3's chassis one of the stiffest having a 50% higher stiffness compared to a benchmark Mercedes-Benz model.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Five completed cars were produced before the US$2,000,000 development program was canceled.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The original projection by AMC called for building 5,000 AMX/3s per year, but the estimated retail price kept increasing.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Some remaining parts from the canceled, second group of five cars were used by erstwhile Bizzarrini collaborator Salvatore Diomante to assemble the sixth car, named and marketed as Sciabola.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Additionally, an open two-seat Spider featuring no weather protection was built in the 1990s using an unfinished AMX/3 modified chassis and the 7th AMX/3, on display at the Autoworld Museum in Belgium, were both finished by Giorgio Giordanengo.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Sales of the two-seat AMX were lower than the numbers AMC executives wanted.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Still, AMC's vice president for styling, Dick Teague, wanted to continue the sports model.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] American Motors' Advanced Design Studio made design proposals for a 1971 AMX and Teague requested – and received permission – to produce a fully working concept car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Starting with a Frost White 1968 AMX coupe as the development mule, Teague updated its front end to the grille and swooping front fenders of what was incorporated into the production 1971 Javelin.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The concept car also featured the interior to what was to become AMC's characteristic high-backed bucket seats and corduroy upholstery introduced in 1970.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The concept car was repainted light metallic blue with red striping to match the interior.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A short-wheelbase, two-seat 1971 AMX was not approved for production by the automaker, but Teague used this car as his daily driver.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The AMX was intended to be a “halo car” for American Motors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Another objective was "lowering the median age of visitors to AMC showrooms; in that role it was a major success" even though however the sales goals not achieved.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] The two-seat AMC AMX has been described as being "a perfect car for many who lusted for the Corvette but could not afford it." Developed under "austere budject" the AMX and the four-seat Javelin were designed to be radical departures from AMC's economy image.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Automotive journalist Patric George noted that the AMC AMX is "great vintage American iron" with only "two seats, making it more of a sports car than a lot of other muscle cars." Automotive historian and author Richard M.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] According to CNN, before 2004, the AMX had been under-appreciated from an investment standpoint.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In 2004, there was considerable variation between the values of two-seat AMXs and four-seat Javelin AMXs.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Craig Fitzgerald mentioned "the satisfaction in owning a car that you don't see every single day, or on the cover of every single magazine." Fitzgerald favored the two-seater because of its rarity, but noted that some parts for either car were expensive.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Unique versions, such as the California 500 Specials and the 52 Hurst-modified SS/AMX drag race cars are perhaps the most highly sought after by collectors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In 2006, a California 500 AMX sold for $54,000 at the Barrett-Jackson auction in Scottsdale, Arizona, while a regular AMX went for over $55,000 at the Mecum collector auction in Belvidere, Illinois.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In 2007, *Hemmings* wrote that only about 39 of the original SS/AMX turn-key race cars may have survived.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] By 2007, the AMX was "among the most highly sought AMC cars" and "really taking off in the muscle-car market".
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In 2008, *Hemmings* wrote buyers had "only recently 'discovered' the AMX; they're now snapping them up left and right.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] In 2010, *Hemmings Classic Car* included the two-seat AMXs in their list of 32 best cars to restore in terms of economic sense after factoring purchase price, parts availability, as well as restored value and desirability.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Although low production, the AMX shared parts and components with other AMC models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] There are many active AMC car clubs for these cars.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Parts, including reproduction components, are available.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] More valuable according to automotive historian and author, James C.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] His book, *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, explains this important and measurable pleasure to an owner, whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage, such as a red 1969 AMX that attracts more attention than the more prestigious Ferraris and Lamborghinis.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] A variety of scale models of the AMX are available, including promotional 1/25-scale model manufactured under license from AMC by Jo-Han in factory colors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Hot Wheels offered a 1969 AMX custom in 1:64 scale, and in 1971 issued the AMX/2 show car model.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] Newer models in 1:18 scale diecast were issued, including the Playboy Pink version in the "Best of the Best" series, as well as the modified "Drag-On Lady" race car.
[src:american-motors-corporation/amc-amx] According to the editors of *Die Cast X Magazine*, "muscle cars are the largest, most popular category in die-cast" collectors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:american-motors-corporation/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
